For any polynomial $P(x)$, $k$ is a zero of $P(x) \Leftrightarrow (x - k)$ is a factor of $P(x)$.

Proof:

$k$ is a zero of $P(x) \Leftrightarrow P(k) = 0$ {definition of a zero}

$\Leftrightarrow R = 0$ {Remainder theorem}

$\Leftrightarrow P(x) = Q(x)(x - k)$ {division algorithm}

$\Leftrightarrow (x - k)$ is a factor of $P(x)$ {definition of a factor}

The Factor theorem says that if 2 is a zero of $P(x)$ then $(x - 2)$ is a factor of $P(x)$, and vice versa.
